{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/880"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36990"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"363"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39213"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 7-day-old male newborn is brought into hospital with failure to pass meconium, abdominal distension, and bile-stained vomiting. The child was born at term via normal vaginal delivery, which was uncomplicated. On examination the only abnormality to be noted is the distended abdomen. A plain abdominal X-ray shows gaseous distension with several air fluid levels throughout the gut.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Volvulus neonatorum","Hirschsprung disease","Meconium ileus","Small bowel atresia","Duodenal obstruction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by failure of colonic ganglion cell migration during gestation, results in segmental failure of the distal colon to relax, causing functional colonic obstruction. It is one of the most common causes of neonatal colonic obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the disease may be diagnosed in adults, the typical presentation is of the male infant with failure to pass meconium, bilious vomiting, and progressive abdominal distention. Early diagnosis is critical in preventing complications such as enterocolitis or colonic rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal X-ray identifying multiple air fluid levels suggestive of distal obstruction should prompt clinical suspicion. Depending on the length of the aganglionotic segment, an area of distal narrowing of the rectum and colon may be evident. Diagnosis can be confirmed with contrast enema or anorectal manometry and histopathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELess common differential diagnoses include ileal atresia, meconium ileus and anorectal malformation. Ileal atresia and meconium ileus would be less likely to be associated with obstruction the length of the gut, as in this case. In small bowel atresia, there would be dilated loops of proximal small bowel with air-fluid levels, and absence of gas distally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E If there was an anorectal malformation this might well be evident with an imperforate anus. In meconium ileus there is usually a paucity of intestinal gas distal to the point of obstruction - which is usually in the terminal ileal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuodenal obstruction and volvulus neonatorium are common causes of upper intestinal obstruction in the neonate, indicated by the double bubble sign and findings of a distended stomach and proximal duodenum with reduced distal bowel gas respectively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Failure to pass meconium and abdominal distension are key signs of Hirschsprung disease."],"references":["Ambartsumyan L, Smith C, Kapur R. Diagnosis of Hirschsprung Disease. Pediatric and Developmental Pathology. 2019;23(1):8-22.","Carlson Merrow A, Hariharan S. Imaging in Pediatrics. Elsevier; 2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36990"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"880"}},"stemMedia":{"da